00:02:42.350 --> 00:02:46.780
Let's take a look,
in more detail, at what Fick taught

00:02:46.780 --> 00:02:51.580
us.
He said that if we have ingress of

00:02:51.580 --> 00:02:56.740
species i into some solid,
the rate of ingress is given by the

00:02:56.740 --> 00:03:01.910
equation shown here which expresses
the flux which is mass per unit time

00:03:01.910 --> 00:03:07.080
per unit cross-sectional area as
proportional to the concentration

00:03:07.080 --> 00:03:12.240
gradient. And the proportionality
constant is the diffusion

00:03:12.240 --> 00:03:17.410
coefficient. And what we see here
is a sketch of what that

00:03:17.410 --> 00:03:22.210
might look like.
Some initial surface concentration

00:03:22.210 --> 00:03:26.640
held constant with ingress of
material. And since the flux is the

00:03:26.640 --> 00:03:31.070
derivative, you can see that the
flux, but for some multiplication

00:03:31.070 --> 00:03:35.490
factor, tracks with the
concentration.

00:03:35.490 --> 00:03:39.920
We have the steepest concentration
gradient at the surface,

00:03:39.920 --> 00:03:44.350
and deep inside the specimen there
is essentially no concentration

00:03:44.350 --> 00:03:48.780
gradient so the flux attenuates.
Flux shown here in fuchsia and

00:03:48.780 --> 00:03:53.630
concentration shown here.
And when I say profile it means

00:03:53.630 --> 00:03:58.900
something as a function of distance.
Profile, in this case, is the

00:03:58.900 --> 00:04:04.180
concentration profile or a flux
profile. You can see those two.

00:04:04.180 --> 00:04:09.450
And then we started looking at some
of the atomistics and reasoned that

00:04:09.450 --> 00:04:14.720
there is some jumping involved.
And with the jumping comes the

00:04:14.720 --> 00:04:32.040
notion of activation.
We looked at this.

00:04:00.000 --> 00:04:24.260
And we concluded that there is an
activation energy associated with

00:04:24.260 --> 00:04:28.530
jumping through that saddle point,
an Arrhenius type behavior, natural

00:04:28.530 --> 00:04:32.790
log of d, linear in reciprocal of
the absolute temperature.

00:04:32.790 --> 00:04:37.060
Remember, this is not the Rydberg
constant, this is the gas constant

00:04:37.060 --> 00:04:41.330
which is the product of the
Boltzmann constant and the Avogadro

00:04:41.330 --> 00:04:45.590
number. And units will give you a
clue as to which to use.

00:04:45.590 --> 00:04:49.860
If the activation energy is in
units per mole then obviously use

00:04:49.860 --> 00:05:09.186
the gas constant.
Otherwise, you use the Boltzmann

00:04:33.800 --> 00:04:37.400
constant. And when we looked at the
atomistics further,

00:04:37.400 --> 00:04:41.000
we reasoned that when we have
diffusion by vacancy jump mechanism,

00:04:41.000 --> 00:04:44.600
this activation energy up here in
the equation is the sum of two

00:04:44.600 --> 00:04:48.200
components, one being the enthalpy
of vacancy formation,

00:04:48.200 --> 00:04:51.800
which is really the negative of the
bonding energy,

00:04:51.800 --> 00:04:55.400
and then the energy associated with
the atom migration which is the

00:04:55.400 --> 00:04:59.000
energy of squeezing through that
saddle point shown in the figure.

00:04:59.000 --> 00:05:23.140
In the case of interstitial
diffusion, we do not have to form

00:05:23.140 --> 00:05:27.280
vacancies. There are enough vacant
sites, by virtue of the fact that we

00:05:27.280 --> 00:05:31.420
have so much free volume,
even in a close-packed solid.

00:05:31.420 --> 00:05:35.560
We are really just paying for the
enthalpy of migration.

00:05:35.560 --> 00:05:39.710
Lastly, we looked at how these two
are related to the degree of

00:05:39.710 --> 00:05:43.850
confinement. In other words,
the atom is restricted by the ease

00:05:43.850 --> 00:06:03.033
with which it can run down its
appropriate raceway.

00:05:28.000 --> 00:05:51.750
And we reasoned that going through
the bulk lattice is the most

00:05:51.750 --> 00:06:11.400
tortuous path and has the highest
activation energy,

00:05:35.500 --> 00:05:59.250
lowest diffusion coefficient.
Grain boundaries have atoms with

00:05:59.250 --> 00:06:18.833
fewer nearest neighbors,
lower coordination number,

00:05:43.000 --> 00:06:06.750
so the diffusion coefficient is
higher in the grain boundary and is

00:06:06.750 --> 00:06:26.933
highest along the free surface.
And we saw last day that the

00:05:50.500 --> 00:06:14.250
diffusion coefficient along the free
surface of a solid approaches values

00:06:14.250 --> 00:06:33.766
equivalent to that of diffusion
in a liquid state.

00:05:58.000 --> 00:06:23.380
What I want to do today is step back
to the continuum and use Fick's law

00:06:23.380 --> 00:06:28.760
to describe what is going on
mathematically in the macro world.

00:06:28.760 --> 00:06:34.150
I want to first start with
diffusion across a membrane.

00:06:34.150 --> 00:06:39.530
This is a membrane of some
thickness L. And I am going to put

00:06:39.530 --> 00:06:44.920
a gas to the left,
P1, and I am going to hold it

00:06:44.920 --> 00:06:50.300
constant. And to the right,
I am going to have a gas at P2 also

00:06:50.300 --> 00:06:55.070
being held constant.
And, just so that we are all on the

00:06:55.070 --> 00:06:59.210
same page, I am going to make P1
greater than P2.

00:06:59.210 --> 00:07:03.350
That means matter will diffuse from
high pressure to low pressure,

00:07:03.350 --> 00:07:07.490
high concentration to low
concentration.

00:07:07.490 --> 00:07:11.640
That means the flux will be left to
right. And we can use the Universal

00:07:11.640 --> 00:07:15.780
Gas Law, pressure volume equals the
product of mole number times gas

00:07:15.780 --> 00:07:19.920
constant times temperature in order
to convert pressure units into

00:07:19.920 --> 00:07:39.440
concentration units.
And we know that the concentration

00:07:04.000 --> 00:07:08.000
of a species i is simply equal to
the mole number i divided by the

00:07:08.000 --> 00:07:12.000
total volume of the system.
This is moles per unit volume,

00:07:12.000 --> 00:07:16.000
so that is a concentration. And so
that means then that if we go to the

00:07:16.000 --> 00:07:20.000
Universal Gas Law that will give us
P over RT. If you take a pressure,

00:07:20.000 --> 00:07:24.000
divide it by the product of the gas
constant and temperature,

00:07:24.000 --> 00:07:28.000
it will move from pressure units to
concentration units.

00:07:28.000 --> 00:07:32.000
And so what I would like to do is
show what this system looks like

00:07:32.000 --> 00:07:56.770
after some period of time.
I am going to put the convention

00:07:56.770 --> 00:08:02.330
with zero on the left surface.
This is distance moving from left

00:08:02.330 --> 00:08:07.880
to right. X equals zero is the left
surface of the membrane.

00:08:07.880 --> 00:08:13.440
X equals L is the right surface of
the membrane. And now let's put

00:08:13.440 --> 00:08:32.146
concentration c1 on the left surface
and c2 on the right surface.

00:07:59.000 --> 00:08:24.810
And what we know is we expect that
after some period of time,

00:08:24.810 --> 00:08:30.630
if c1 is held constant and c2 is
held constant then,

00:08:30.630 --> 00:08:36.450
after some period of time,
we expect to have a profile that is

00:08:36.450 --> 00:08:42.270
linear. And we should be able to
infer that from Fick's First Law.

00:08:42.270 --> 00:08:48.090
We know that Fick's First Law tells
us that J is equal to

00:08:48.090 --> 00:09:05.646
minus D, dc by dx.
If I am holding the concentrations

00:08:34.000 --> 00:08:40.000
on both sides constant then it tells
me then that the gradient is going

00:08:40.000 --> 00:08:46.000
to be constant.
Otherwise, I have some sources or

00:08:46.000 --> 00:08:52.000
sinks which we do not allow for.
After this short time we have this

00:08:52.000 --> 00:08:58.000
profile which we term steady state.
And it is termed steady state

00:08:58.000 --> 00:09:03.000
because it is invariant with time.
The flux is not a function of time.

00:09:03.000 --> 00:09:07.000
The flux entering the free surface
on the left equals the flux exiting

00:09:07.000 --> 00:09:11.000
on the free surface on the right.
And, therefore, the flux must be

00:09:11.000 --> 00:09:15.000
constant throughout the membrane.
Because if J is constant, and I am

00:09:15.000 --> 00:09:19.000
assuming that the diffusion
coefficient doesn't change with time,

00:09:19.000 --> 00:09:23.000
then it means that this gradient
must be constant.

00:09:23.000 --> 00:09:27.000
The slope must be the same all the
way along, reinforcing the notion

00:09:27.000 --> 00:09:31.000
that we have a straight
line profile.

00:09:31.000 --> 00:09:55.140
Now, there is one assumption here,
of course. And that is that the

00:09:55.140 --> 00:09:59.280
diffusion coefficient is independent
of concentration.

00:09:59.280 --> 00:10:03.420
It could be. And we will return to
that later and see what happens if

00:10:03.420 --> 00:10:07.560
we have the concentration depend on
diffusivity. We can describe at

00:10:07.560 --> 00:10:11.710
steady state everything we need to
know about the behavior of this

00:10:11.710 --> 00:10:15.850
system with Fick's First Law alone.
Fick's First Law alone is

00:10:15.850 --> 00:10:36.166
sufficient. What are the kinds of
things that we might want to know?

00:10:00.000 --> 00:10:25.810
We might want to ask how much
material diffuses over time,

00:10:25.810 --> 00:10:31.630
mass per unit time passing through
the membrane. All we need is Fick's

00:10:31.630 --> 00:10:37.450
First Law because we know that we
can say that the mass will simply

00:10:37.450 --> 00:10:43.270
equal the flux,
which is mass per unit area per unit

00:10:43.270 --> 00:10:49.090
time. If I know the total area of
the membrane and I know the time

00:10:49.090 --> 00:10:54.420
then that is all I need.
Fick's First Law is very thorough in

00:10:54.420 --> 00:10:59.280
describing a system at steady state.
Last thing about this concentration

00:10:59.280 --> 00:11:04.140
profile, the operative definition of
steady state is that J does not

00:11:04.140 --> 00:11:08.990
change with time.
In other words, if I look at this

00:11:08.990 --> 00:11:13.850
at some later time,
as long as I maintain constant end

00:11:13.850 --> 00:11:18.710
compositions, I will have this same
profile. But suppose I had a

00:11:18.710 --> 00:11:23.570
situation like this where the
diffusion coefficient is not

00:11:23.570 --> 00:11:42.373
independent of concentration.
I will give you an example.

00:11:08.500 --> 00:11:13.500
The diffusion coefficient of carbon
in iron, this is steel,

00:11:13.500 --> 00:11:18.500
as a function of the concentration
of carbon in iron.

00:11:18.500 --> 00:11:23.500
It turns out that as more and more
carbon goes into iron,

00:11:23.500 --> 00:11:28.500
the diffusion coefficient changes.
You would expect that because now

00:11:28.500 --> 00:11:33.000
some of the sites are occupied.
Which is it? Do you think that the

00:11:33.000 --> 00:11:37.000
diffusion coefficient,
as you get more and more carbon into

00:11:37.000 --> 00:11:41.000
iron, starts to fall like this,
or do you think the diffusion

00:11:41.000 --> 00:11:45.000
coefficient rises like this so that
at higher concentrations it becomes

00:11:45.000 --> 00:11:49.000
more difficult to diffuse?
Well, this might sound appealing

00:11:49.000 --> 00:11:53.000
because the sites are getting
blocked. It make sense.

00:11:53.000 --> 00:11:57.000
There are fewer empty sites.
But, in point of fact, the

00:11:57.000 --> 00:12:01.000
diffusion coefficient
actually rises.

00:12:01.000 --> 00:12:25.570
Why? Well, I have told you that the
carbon atom is larger than the

00:12:25.570 --> 00:12:30.140
interstitial site.
When the carbons go into the

00:12:30.140 --> 00:12:34.710
interstitial sites they act as
wedges, and they actually wedge open

00:12:34.710 --> 00:12:39.280
the system and make it easier for
the succeeding atoms to diffuse

00:12:39.280 --> 00:12:43.850
through. In point of fact,
this is what happens. But it could

00:12:43.850 --> 00:12:48.420
be either. Let's imagine,
suppose we have case number one,

00:12:48.420 --> 00:13:07.840
where the diffusion coefficient
falls as concentration rises.

00:12:33.000 --> 00:12:38.500
And now I have a steady state
concentration profile.

00:12:38.500 --> 00:12:44.000
I have c1 constant on the left,
c2 constant on the right, and here

00:12:44.000 --> 00:12:49.500
is the equation we have to look at.
Minus D, dc by dx. But this is now

00:12:49.500 --> 00:12:55.000
a function of concentration.
If I have case number one, when I

00:12:55.000 --> 00:13:00.500
have the highest concentration up
here, if this is going to remain

00:13:00.500 --> 00:13:06.000
constant, if the concentration
dependence of the diffusion

00:13:06.000 --> 00:13:11.500
coefficient says D is low when c is
high then that suggests to keep a

00:13:11.500 --> 00:13:17.000
constant flux, dc/dx must
be high when c is high.

00:13:17.000 --> 00:13:40.750
That means instead of a straight
line, we are going to see something

00:13:40.750 --> 00:14:00.000
that looks like this.
This is case number one.

00:13:24.500 --> 00:13:48.250
How about case number two where the
concentration dependence of the

00:13:48.250 --> 00:14:06.900
diffusivity is indicated
with a rise?

00:13:32.000 --> 00:13:57.090
Well, that means at high
concentration my diffusion

00:13:57.090 --> 00:14:02.180
coefficient is going to be higher
than it is at low concentration.

00:14:02.180 --> 00:14:07.270
If this number is higher at high
concentration then this number has

00:14:07.270 --> 00:14:12.360
to be lower so that the product will
remain constant.

00:14:12.360 --> 00:14:17.450
This is case number two.
These are all variants of steady

00:14:17.450 --> 00:14:22.230
state. J is not a function of time.
J is independent of time.

00:14:22.230 --> 00:14:26.700
Now I want to ask what happens in
that initial moment when we first

00:14:26.700 --> 00:14:31.170
pressurize the system.
Let's say we start off and there is

00:14:31.170 --> 00:14:35.640
nothing inside the membrane.
Just to keep things simple, I am

00:14:35.640 --> 00:14:40.110
going to make P equal zero on the
right-hand side.

00:14:40.110 --> 00:14:44.580
Left side is P1.
And at time zero,

00:14:44.580 --> 00:14:49.050
we initially pressurize so we have a
concentration c1 instantly at the

00:14:49.050 --> 00:14:53.520
surface. What is the set of events
that occurs leading up to the

00:14:53.520 --> 00:15:11.773
establishment of the steady
state profile?

00:14:38.000 --> 00:15:02.160
I would expect,
after a short time,

00:15:02.160 --> 00:15:06.330
we would see concentration profile
shown like this.

00:15:06.330 --> 00:15:10.490
And then after a longer period of
time like this.

00:15:10.490 --> 00:15:14.660
And then after a longer period of
time like this.

00:15:14.660 --> 00:15:18.830
And then finally,
of course, we establish.

00:15:18.830 --> 00:15:37.526
This is time is increasing from low
to high.

00:15:03.000 --> 00:15:27.150
This could be t1,
t2, t3. And so we can then say

00:15:27.150 --> 00:15:31.300
let's park ourselves at some value
x1 on zero to L.

00:15:31.300 --> 00:15:35.460
And look at what is happening.
Initially, if I take the slope it

00:15:35.460 --> 00:15:39.610
is a low number.
If I take the slope at a later time

00:15:39.610 --> 00:15:43.760
it is a higher number.
If I take the slope at a later time

00:15:43.760 --> 00:15:47.920
it is an even higher number.
And, ultimately, it is going to be

00:15:47.920 --> 00:16:07.240
as high as the steady state value.
I could take that data set and plot

00:15:33.200 --> 00:15:39.600
the flux at x equals x1.
I am sitting here watching the

00:15:39.600 --> 00:15:46.000
profile evolve with time.
Initially, it is zero because there

00:15:46.000 --> 00:16:12.400
is nothing in the membrane.
And then it slowly rises and

00:16:12.400 --> 00:16:30.133
reaches the steady state value.
This is J at steady state here,

00:15:58.800 --> 00:16:24.150
and this could be t1, t2 and t3.
You can see that coming off the

00:16:24.150 --> 00:16:28.460
slope. Clearly,
when we are moving through this time

00:16:28.460 --> 00:16:32.760
period, J is very much a function of
time. Because,

00:16:32.760 --> 00:16:37.070
if you close your eyes and wait,
you will see that the profile has

00:16:37.070 --> 00:16:41.380
changed. And,
if the profile has changed,

00:16:41.380 --> 00:16:45.690
it means that the instant value of
flux has changed.

00:16:45.690 --> 00:17:05.046
Flux is a function of time,
so this is not steady state.

00:16:30.000 --> 00:16:55.450
Instead it is transient.
We are in the transient regime.

00:16:55.450 --> 00:17:00.900
And so, as is always the case, we
can draw these curves.

00:17:00.900 --> 00:17:06.360
They start at a high value,
they attenuate to zero. What is the

00:17:06.360 --> 00:17:11.810
magical question?
What is the shape?

00:17:11.810 --> 00:17:17.270
That is the only reason I need math,
to tell me the shape of those curves.

00:17:17.270 --> 00:17:35.773
Is this an exponential decay?
Is this half of a sinusoid?

00:17:02.500 --> 00:17:07.500
What is the shape of the curves?
I want to know c versus x at all

00:17:07.500 --> 00:17:12.500
times because it is changing as a
function of time.

00:17:12.500 --> 00:17:17.500
That means I need to know c is a
function of x and t.

00:17:17.500 --> 00:17:22.500
I have got to solve this.
And Fick gave us the solution to

00:17:22.500 --> 00:17:27.500
this as well. The solution to this
is the solution to an equation known

00:17:27.500 --> 00:17:32.500
as Fick's Second Law.
Let's look at Fick's Second Law.

00:17:32.500 --> 00:17:37.500
I am going to write it in the
special case when D is independent

00:17:37.500 --> 00:17:42.500
of composition.
D has to be independent of

00:17:42.500 --> 00:17:47.500
composition for me to do what I am
going to do next.

00:17:47.500 --> 00:17:52.500
And it is a pretty good assumption
in many industrial settings.

00:17:52.500 --> 00:17:57.500
And so I am just going to write it.
It is a partial differential

00:17:57.500 --> 00:18:22.410
equation.
What it is telling you is that the

00:18:22.410 --> 00:18:27.240
partial, with respect to time,
is equal to the product of the

00:18:27.240 --> 00:18:32.080
diffusion coefficient times the
partial of the gradient in

00:18:32.080 --> 00:18:36.910
concentration.
And so, clearly,

00:18:36.910 --> 00:18:41.740
this is a partial differential
equation. And that is bad.

00:18:41.740 --> 00:18:46.580
You cannot solve this one, not yet.
But the good news is it is a linear

00:18:46.580 --> 00:18:51.810
partial differential equation.
That is good because I can show you

00:18:51.810 --> 00:18:57.450
a solution that applies for a given
setting, and then you can play with

00:18:57.450 --> 00:19:03.090
the boundary conditions and use the
same solution.

00:19:03.090 --> 00:19:08.720
That is the good news,
